#7 — Ensure that legacy service users use key pair authentication

Severity: High | Scanner: CIS Benchmarks
Current State: Legacy service users have no RSA key pair configured — the flip side of #1/#2.
Remediation:

Generate 2048-bit RSA key pair per service user
ALTER USER <user> SET RSA_PUBLIC_KEY='<key>'
Switch app to private key connection
Disable password after validation
Set 180-day rotation reminder (ties to #10/#11)


Difficulty: Hard — same coordination cost as #1
Side-Effect Score: 8/10
Remediation Risk: Service interruption during cutover. Worst case: Production outage.
Risk of Not Fixing: Service accounts typically hold broad data access. Worst case: Account compromise → mass data exfiltration.

Prerequisites: Weak/leaked password • Broad access scope • No IP restrictions


Audit Exception: Rolled into unified migration plan with #1/#2; network policy + complexity rules + login monitoring as compensating controls.


🟡 Group 2: Planned Initiatives
#3 — Stored procedures owned by ACCOUNTADMIN/SECURITYADMIN

Severity: High | Scanner: CIS Benchmarks
Current State: Some SPs are owned by ACCOUNTADMIN/SECURITYADMIN, meaning callers can inherit excessive privilege via owner's-rights execution.
Remediation:

SHOW PROCEDURES and filter by owner
Create dedicated functional role (e.g., SP_OWNER_ROLE)
GRANT OWNERSHIP ON PROCEDURE ... TO ROLE <functional_role>
Validate execution + dependencies
Add RBAC guardrails to prevent recurrence


Difficulty: Med — operationally simple but requires per-SP dependency analysis
Side-Effect Score: 5/10
Remediation Risk: SP may fail if internal logic depends on admin-only privileges. Worst case: Critical scheduled job breaks.
Risk of Not Fixing: SQL injection or malicious modification executes with admin rights. Worst case: Attacker hijacks SP, gains full account control, wipes audit logs.

Prerequisites: Injectable SP • Attacker can trigger execution • No SP change monitoring


Audit Exception: Legacy artifacts from initial deployment; access to call these SPs already restricted by role. Ownership migration scheduled Q[X].

#4 — SPs owned by ACCOUNTADMIN/SECURITYADMIN (duplicate of #3)

Severity: High | Scanner: CIS Benchmarks
Same issue, second detection. Handle in the same effort as #3.

#5 — SPs run with ACCOUNTADMIN/SECURITYADMIN privileges

Severity: High | Scanner: CIS Benchmarks
Current State: SPs configured with EXECUTE AS OWNER where owner is a high-privilege role. Anyone who can call the SP effectively gets admin powers — worse than a shared password.
Remediation:

Audit EXECUTE AS settings across all SPs
Switch to EXECUTE AS CALLER or transfer ownership to lower-privilege role
Refactor SPs that genuinely need elevated privilege to use a dedicated, narrowly-scoped role
Add SP privilege checks to CI/CD pipeline


Difficulty: Hard — requires deep understanding of each SP's business logic
Side-Effect Score: 6/10
Remediation Risk: Permission model change may break previously-working operations. Worst case: Multiple business-critical SPs fail simultaneously, halting data processing.
Risk of Not Fixing: Privilege escalation vector — any caller becomes a de facto admin. Worst case: Low-privilege user calls SP → bypasses all access controls.

Prerequisites: USAGE granted broadly • Exploitable internal logic (e.g., dynamic SQL) • No call auditing


Audit Exception: SPs perform genuinely privileged operations (e.g., cross-schema data movement); caller list restricted; ACCESS_HISTORY tracking enabled. Refactoring in planning.

